{"cursor":"55729","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n\n{{Infobox monarch |name = Ashoka |title =Maurya Samrat |image = Chakravatin.JPG\n|caption = A \"Chakravartin\" ruler, 1st century BCE/CE. Andhra Pradesh,\nAmaravati. Preserved at Musee Guimet |reign = 268â232 BCE |coronation = 268 BCE\n|other titles = Samraat Chakravartin; other titles include Devanampriya and\nPriyadarsin |religion = Buddhism |predecessor = Bindusara |successor = Dasaratha\n|spouse 1=Kaurwaki |spouse 2 =Devi |spouse 3 =Padmavati |spouse 4 =Tishyaraksha\n|children =Mahendra, Sanghamitra, Tivala, Kunala, Jaluka, Charumati |dynasty =\nMaurya |father = Bindusara |mother = Maharani Dharma or Shubhadrangi |brothers =\nVitthashoka (Tissa), Susima |birth_date = 304 BCE |birth_place = Pataliputra,\nPatna |death_date = 232 BCE (aged 72) |death_place = Pataliputra, Patna |date of\nburial = Cremated 232 BCE, less than 24 hours after death |place of burial =\nAshes immersed in the Ganges River, possibly at Varanasi |influenced by = Buddha\nChandragupta Maurya Bindusara Chanakya MahaviraAlexandar Seleucus I Nicator\nDiodotus I Antiochus I Soter |influenced = Kunal Harsha Samudragupta Ramagupta\nChandragupta II Kumaragupta Skandagupta Purugupta Vishnugupta }}\n\n'Ashoka Maurya' (304â232 BCE) commonly known as 'Ashoka' and also as 'Ashoka\nthe Great', was an Indian emperor of the Maurya Dynasty who ruled almost all of\nthe Indian subcontinent from ca. 269 BCE to 232 BCE. Thapur (1973), p.\n51. One of India's greatest emperors, Ashoka reigned over most of present-\nday India after a number of military conquests. His empire stretched from the\nmodern Iranian provinces of Khorasan, Sistan and Balochistan (unpartitioned),\nthrough the Hindu Kush mountains in Afghanistan, to present-day Bangladesh and\nthe Indian state of Assam in the east, and as far south as northern Kerala and\nAndhra Pradesh. The empire had Taxila, Ujjain and Pataliputra as its capital.\nIn about 260 BCE Ashoka waged a bitterly destructive war against the state of\nKalinga (modern Odisha). Jerry Bentley, Old World\nEncounters: Cross-Cultural Contacts and Exchanges in Pre-Modern Times (New\nYork: Oxford University Press, 1993), 44. He conquered Kalinga, which\nnone of his ancestors (starting from Chandragupta Maurya) had done. His reign\nwas headquartered in Magadha (present-day Bihar). He embraced Buddhism after\nwitnessing the mass deaths of the Kalinga War, which he himself had waged out\nof a desire for conquest. \"Ashoka reflected on the war in Kalinga, which\nreportedly had resulted in more than 100,000 deaths and 150,000\ndeportations.\" Jerry Bentley, Old World Encounters: Cross-Cultural Contacts\nand Exchanges in Pre-Modern Times (New York: Oxford University Press, 1993),\n45. Ashoka converted gradually to Buddhism beginning about 263 BCE at the\nlatest. He was later dedicated to the\npropagation of Buddhism across Asia, and established monuments marking several\nsignificant sites in the life of Gautama Buddha. \"Ashoka regarded Buddhism as a\ndoctrine that could serve as a cultural foundation for political\nunity.\" Jerry Bentley, Old World Encounters: Cross-Cultural Contacts and\nExchanges in Pre-Modern Times (New York: Oxford University Press, 1993),\n46. Ashoka is now remembered as a philanthropic administrator. In the\nKalinga edicts, he addresses his people as his \"children\", and mentions that as\na father he desires their good.\n\nAshoka is referred to as [[Samraat]] [[Chakravartin]] Ashoka â the \"Emperor of\nEmperors Ashoka.\" His name \"\" means \"painless, without sorrow\" in Sanskrit (the\n''a'' privativum and Åoka \"pain, distress\"). In his edicts, he is referred to as\n{{IAST|DevÄnÄmpriya}} (Pali {{IAST|DevÄnaá¹piya}} or \"The Beloved of the Gods\"),\nand {{IAST|PriyadarÅin}} (Pali {{IAST|PiyadasÄ«}} or \"He who regards everyone\nwith affection\"). His fondness for his name's connection to the Saraca asoca\ntree, or the \"Asoka tree\" is also referenced in the Ashokavadana.\n\nH.G. Wells wrote of Ashoka in A Short History of the World (H. G. Wells):\n\nAlong with the Edicts of Ashoka, his legend is related in the 2nd-century\n[[Ashokavadana]] (\"Narrative of Asoka,\" a part of [[Divyavadana]]), and in the\nSri Lankan text [[Mahavamsa]] (\"Great Chronicle\").\n\nAshoka played a critical role in helping make Buddhism a world\nreligion. Bruce Rich. [http://www.tibethouse.us/programs/view/102312/4 To\nUphold The World Author Discussion] The emblem of the modern Republic of\nIndia is an adaptation of the Lion Capital of Ashoka.\n","linknr":1086,"url":"Ashoka_the_Great","recorded":1374547239,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Ashoka&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Ashoka&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","/wiki/Ashoka","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","/w/index.php?title=Ashoka_the_Great&redirect=no","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/Ashoka:_Innovators_for_the_Public","/wiki/Mauryan_dynasty","/wiki/File:Chakravatin.JPG","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/60/Chakravatin.JPG/220px-Chakravatin.JPG","/wiki/Chakravartin","/wiki/Pataliputra","/wiki/Patna","/wiki/Pataliputra","/wiki/Patna","/wiki/Ganges","/wiki/Varanasi","/wiki/Cremated","/wiki/Bindusara","/wiki/Dasaratha_Maurya","/wiki/Kaurwaki","/w